{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/366"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.07,0.11,0.1,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45359"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/366"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30273"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44024"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45359"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department after repeated episodes of syncope. He reports no chest pain or dyspnoea. He has no significant medical history and is an active sports player. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 60/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, and SpO2 99% on room air. His pulse is sharp-rising and jerky. His JVP has a prominent a wave. A double apical impulse is present. There is a high-pitched, crescendo-decrescendo midsystolic murmur heard best over the lower left sternal edge that radiates to the apex. The murmur is augmented by Valsalva and diminished by squatting. His chest is clear on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his murmur?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy","Mild mitral regurgitation","Moderate tricuspid regurgitation","Congenital ventricular septal defect","Severe aortic stenosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy (HOCM)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. The left ventricular outflow tract obstruction pathognomonic of HOCM is dynamic; the degree of obstruction is largely dependent on loading conditions and cardiac contractility. Manoeuvres that decrease left ventricular volume (Valsalva, standing from a squatting position) will augment a HOCM murmur, while manoeuvres which increase preload (rapid squatting) or afterload (hand-grip) will decrease the intensity of a HOCM murmur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMild mitral regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E is a pansystolic murmur heard best over the apex that radiates to the axilla. It is accentuated by the hand-grip manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModerate tricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E is a pansystolic murmur heard best over the lower left sternal edge that increases with inspiration. It is often seen with features of pulmonary hypertension, such as a loud P2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Econgenital ventricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E is a harsh holosystolic murmur heard best over the lower left sternal edge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere aortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a crescendo-decrescendo systolic ejection murmur heard best over the upper right sternal border that radiates to the carotids. It is diminished by the Valsalva manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The left ventricular outflow tract obstruction pathognomonic of HOCM is dynamic; the degree of obstruction is largely dependent on loading conditions and cardiac contractility."],"references":["Veselka J, Anavekar N, Charron P. Hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy. The Lancet. 2017;389(10075):1253-1267."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30273"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30273"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-13T20:51:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-13T20:51:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"366"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45359"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{